paragraphs.title: 1. DESCRIPTION & VERSION CONTROL
paragraphs.text:
%md


This use case is based on Credit History dataset containing a large amount of features used to determine the quality of loans: bad or good.

 
| Version | Date | Description |
|:------|:------------|:-------------|
| 1.0 | Jul 5, 2018 | Initial Version |
| 0.1 | Jul 1, 2018 | Prep Version |

## Content
2. **Import dataset**
3. **Set Feature roles**
4. **Import XGBoost model**
5. **Model Composition**
3. **Analyzing the model for monotonicity**
4. **Explaining the model in general**
5. **Explaining specific predictions**

The FxAI APIs are Python, and due to a handful of external libraries, require Python 2.7, which is available in Analytics Workbench today via the `%python` interpreter. (The `%pyspark` interpreter runs Python 3.4.)

paragraphs.title: Select Model and Dataset Folder
paragraphs.text:
%python
import os 
import time

files_list = []
root = 'xai_model_files'
for file in os.listdir(root):
    files_list.append((file, file + ' - ' + str(time.ctime(os.path.getmtime(root + '/' + file)))))
    

sel_folder = z.select("Select folder name", files_list)

paragraphs.title: Select sample weight column name
paragraphs.text:
%python
wt_col_name = z.select("",[('None', 'None')] + [(x,x) for x in df.columns.values])
column_names = list(df.columns.values)

test_w = None
train_w = None
if wt_col_name != 'None':
    weight = [wt_col_name]
    train_w = df[weight].as_matrix()
    test_w = test_df[weight].as_matrix().ravel()
    column_names.remove(wt_col_name)

column_names.remove(target_col_name)

x = df[column_names].as_matrix()
y = df[target].as_matrix()

train_x = x
train_y = y
feature_names = column_names

test_df = pd.read_csv(test_file_loc)
test_x = test_df[column_names].as_matrix()
test_y = test_df[target].as_matrix()

import xgboost as xgb
dtrain = xgb.DMatrix(train_x, train_y, weight=train_w, feature_names=feature_names)
dtest = xgb.DMatrix(test_x, test_y, weight=test_w, feature_names=feature_names)

paragraphs.title: Model Performance
paragraphs.text:
%python
import pickle
#Set the location of the new packages from xai installation
#in 'sys' path

model = pickle.load(open(root + '/' + sel_folder + '/xgboost_model.pkl'))

import sys
sys.path.append('/var/lib/zeppelin/.local/lib/python2.7/site-packages')
from xai import xgb_explanation_api as xgbapi

dtest = xgb.DMatrix(test_x, weight=test_w, feature_names=feature_names)
pred_proba_y = model.predict(dtest)
xgbapi.model_perf_eval(test_y, pred_proba_y, sample_weight=test_w)

#Also calculate the accuracy
preds = model.predict(dtest)

acc = accuracy_score(test_y, np.round(preds), sample_weight=test_w)
orig_acc = acc

paragraphs.title: 6. ANALYZING MONOTONICITY
paragraphs.text:
%md
Monotonic relationship between the features and the prediction probability using Pearson's Correlation.
The monotonic strength is a value between 1 (strong) and 0 (weak).

paragraphs.title: Monotonically increasing features
paragraphs.text:
%python
d_x = xgb.DMatrix(x, y, weight=train_w, feature_names=feature_names)
predictions = model.predict(d_x)

import monotonicity.monotonicity_discovery as md

mdisco = md.MonotonictyDiscovery(x, predictions, list(feature_names))
mdisco.check()
mdisco.plot_increasing()

paragraphs.title: Distance To Target Threshold
paragraphs.text:
%python
from xai.xgb_distance_to_target_threshold import XGBDistanceToTargetThreshold
from xai.rf_distance_to_target_threshold import RFDistanceToTargetThreshold

threshold = z.input('Target Threshold', '0.7')

def proba_positive_class(pX):
    xdmatrix = xgb.DMatrix(pX, feature_names=model.feature_names)
    val = model.predict(xdmatrix)
    return np.reshape(val, (-1, 1))

dttt = XGBDistanceToTargetThreshold(model, feature_names, float(threshold), x, dats, proba_positive_class_fn=proba_positive_class)
dttt.visualize_distance_to_target()
